item.description:
Facilitator Resources

In this unit, we've curated the top resources that you, our favorite facilitators, have told us are the most helpful in planning, organizing, and successfully running your SmartLab. If you're looking for documentation that isn't posted here, we kindly remind you that all facilitators have access to the SmartLab Facilitator Resources course which is a robust repository of all things SmartLab and LearningHub.

If you're looking for specific kit, equipment, technology, or software there's a comprehensive SmartLab Technology Resources course with all of the product information you might need (and more).

As a quick note: these resources are created and visible just for you, and are hidden from student view. 

Suggest new technology!

We are always looking for new products to add to the SmartLab lineup. If you have an awesome product idea that you would love to see in the SmartLab, send it our way using this suggestion form. We'd love to see what you've found!

  5. When might you place objects into groups?

item.description:
Before you start the challenge, make a plan for your project and set a SMART goal. Your goal should be Specific, Measurable, Attainable, Relevant, and Time Based.

  1. Planning task: Think about your app. Brainstorm what kind of app you will design including the shapes you will use for icons and what other featured pages, or screens, you will make.
  2. Questions to consider:
    • What is the purpose of your app? Why will other people want to use it?
    • What will you name your app?
    • What will you include in your additional slides, or screens?
    • Will your app have one theme, or will each slide or screen have a different theme?
    • If you could, would you include games? What kind?
  3. Write your project SMART Goal: We will use (name of technology) to (detailed description) by (due date). We are creating this because (personal interest or purpose).

item.description:
Use this space to answer the following questions every day by collaborating with your partner - this is a group assignment.

  1. What did we do today?
  2. What did we learn?
  3. What math did we use?
  4. What could we have done differently?
  5. What new questions do we have based on our work today/this week?
  6. What is our plan for next time?
item.title: Daily Project Journal - Google Slides: Create Your Own App

item.description:
For your project submission share the following items:

  1. Upload the following:
    • Outline of app layout
    • Google Slides presentation of your app
    • Feedback or data from your testing
  2. Reflect on the following questions:
    • How did you decide what to include in your app?
    • What age group were you designing your app for?
    • What would you change or do differently if you had the chance to redesign or redo the app?
    • Which step in the design process was most challenging?
    • Technology is being updated and created to meet the new needs of individuals and companies. Technology is also used to improve what was already made with the newest technology. While planning your app, how did you make sure your app would meet a new need or improve a technology for the people who use it?
  3. Revisit your SMART goal. Remember, your goal should be Specific, Measurable, Attainable, Relevant, and Time Based.
    • Did you meet your Smart goal? Why or why not?
    • How did you manage your time? How could you improve your time management?
    • Did you have to modify your SMART goal?
    • What will you do differently next time?

  1. What did we do today?

  4. What could we have done differently?

item.description:
For your project submission share the following items: 

  1. Upload an image of your code. Make sure the multiplication Operator blocks can be seen in the screenshot. 
  2. Reflect on the following questions:
    • How did the multiplication Operator blocks affect your script?
    • How did Scratch help you solve multiplication problems?
    • Can you think of other ways to change scripts by using Operator blocks? 
    • Are there any other Scratch programs that you would like to write?
  3. Revisit your SMART goal. Remember, your goal should be Specific, Measurable, Attainable, Relevant, and Time Based.
    • Did you meet your SMART goal? Why or why not?
    • How did you manage your time? How could you improve your time management?
    • Did you have to modify your SMART goal?
    • What will you do differently next time?
